				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Avatar of Dust<a name="58836"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 24 04 4:18 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hi, just me looking for spoilers again.  Actually, I have numerous spoilers and what I am looking for is an explanation.  The common strats on the Spider Island ring for Plane of Air basically say you clear the island and then these 20 blue con spiders head for your raid.  Now, one strat I read said to have a druid kite them away while another said to have enchanters chain stun them.  In both cases, that's left totally open-ended -- do you chain-stun/kite these 20 spiders for the rest of the ring event?  Why don't you combine the chain stunning with judicious multi-tank whacking and kill them all?  I am still seeking an explanation of why you just hold these things at some risk for a long period of time.
<br />

<br />
Second, the three red con spiders - I think they are Vorladian Archwalkers - are brought to the raid one at a time, killed, and they split into 3 (or 4) Vorladian Spawn, also red cons.  Every write-up I have seen says you have most people back off the Archwalker before he dies and have a small team finish him off and die.  A bard leads the Spawns away, you rez the suicide team, and the bard highsuns the Spawns back to the raid one at a time for killing, then you repeat this with the other two Archwalkers. (All the while, apparently having your enchanters chain stun the 20 blue con spiders at another location???)  So am I to understand that the Vorladian Spawn that come out of the Archwalker are just so badass that no one can multi-tank them under any circumstances?  They have no AE or proc effects listed, no data on how hard they hit - but apparently off-tanking them is completely out of the question?  Help me out here, those of you who have some familiarity with the event.  I understand what they say to do, but I really want to know why.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
